Part 1:Dataset Selection and Justificat¶

I chose a dataset of bad_password. Passowrds are important for securing important stuff wether it on phone or on web we use passowrds in our daily life bad passwords can result in the can provide helpful knowledge into user behaviour and potential security holes. columns: 1)password: in our dataset we are using passwords as string as interger 2)offline_crack_sec:the time taken in seconds to crack passwords justification: 1)awareness:Testing the bad passwords can help us raise awareness about the about the security of the user or the company.seeing a common pattern in our weak passwords it can help both the user and orgranization as well for better password procedures. 2)vulnerablity:discovering the dataset might undercover flaws and patters which are used by the hackers. The data is useful because it can help in imporving security. 3)user_behavior:revewing at bad_passwords tell us information of the user behavior when it comes to the password creation. The user should create strong and unique password. https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/sujaykapadnis/bad-passwords-never-use-them

import pandas as pd

df = pd.read_csv('bad_passwords.csv')

# Replace non-numeric values with NaN  
df['offline_crack_sec'] = pd.to_numeric(df['offline_crack_sec'], errors='coerce')

# Filter dataframe to only rows with valid numbers
numeric_df = df[df['offline_crack_sec'].notnull()]  

# Select only the numeric columns
numeric_cols = ['value', 'offline_crack_sec', 'rank_alt', 'strength', 'font_size']
corr_matrix = numeric_df[numeric_cols].corr()  

print(corr_matrix)

import pandas as pd

# Assuming you have a DataFrame named df with a 'category' column
df = pd.read_csv("bad_passwords.csv")

category_counts = df['category'].value_counts()

# Create a pie chart
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))
plt.pie(category_counts, labels=category_counts.index, autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=90, colors=['skyblue', 'salmon', 'lightgreen', 'orange'])

# Move the legend outside the pie chart
plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')

plt.title('Distribution of Categories')

# Adjust layout for better readability
plt.tight_layout()

plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Assuming you have a DataFrame named df with a 'category' column
df = pd.read_csv("bad_passwords.csv")

category_counts = df['category'].value_counts()

# Create a pie chart
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))
plt.pie(category_counts, labels=category_counts.index, autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=90, colors=['skyblue', 'salmon', 'lightgreen', 'orange'])

# Move the legend outside the pie chart
plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')

plt.title('Distribution of Categories')

# Adjust layout for better readability
plt.tight_layout()

plt.show()
